subsection.p:
       matrix addition 
       matrix, scalar multiplication 
      This means that we may define scalar multiplication and matrix
      addition operations using the corresponding vector operations.

	\begin{aligned}
	a\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
	\vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp \vvec_n
	\end{array}
	\right]
	{}={} \amp
	\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
	a\vvec_1 \amp a\vvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp a\vvec_n
	\end{array}
	\right] \\
	\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
	\vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp \vvec_n
	\end{array}
	\right]
	{}+{} \amp
	\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
	\wvec_1 \amp \wvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp \wvec_n
	\end{array}
	\right]
	 \\
	{}={} \amp
	\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
	\vvec_1+\wvec_1 \amp \vvec_2+\wvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp
	\vvec_n+\wvec_n 
	\end{array}
	\right]. \\
	\end{aligned}

statement.p:
Suppose we have the matrix A and vector \xvec as given below.
A = \left[\begin{array}{rr} -2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right], \xvec = \left[\begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 3 \\ \end{array}\right] . Their product will be defined to be the linear combination of the columns of A using the components of \xvec as weights. This means that
\begin{aligned} A\xvec = \left[\begin{array}{rr} -2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \left[\begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 3 \\ \end{array}\right] {}={} \amp 2 \left[\begin{array}{r} -2 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ \end{array}\right] + 3 \left[\begin{array}{r} 3 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \\ \\ {}={} \amp \left[\begin{array}{r} -4 \\ 0 \\ 6 \\ \end{array}\right] + \left[\begin{array}{r} 9 \\ 6 \\ 3 \\ \end{array}\right] \\ \\ {}={} \amp \left[\begin{array}{r} 5 \\ 6 \\ 9 \\ \end{array}\right]. \\ \end{aligned}

li.p:
We have

  \begin{alignedat}{2}
  \left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
  1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\
  2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \\
  -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \\
  \end{array}\right]
  \amp
  \fourvec{3}{1}{-1}{1} \\
  \amp =
  \threevec{3(1)+1(2)-1(0)+1(-1)}
  {3(2)+1(4)-1(-3)+1(-2)}
  {3(-1)+1(-2)-1(6)+1(1)} \\
  \amp =\threevec{4}{11}{10}\text{.}
  \end{alignedat}

If A\xvec=\bvec, then we have
\begin{alignedat}{3} x_1 \amp {}+{} \amp 2x_2 \amp {}={} \amp 6 \\ -x_1 \amp {}+{} \amp x_2 \amp {}={} \amp 0\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
with corresponding augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 2 \amp 6 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This means that \xvec=\twovec{2}{2} is the unique solution to the equation A\xvec=\bvec.

 If A and \bvec are as below, write the
	linear system corresponding to the equation
	A\xvec=\bvec. 

	  A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
	  3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
	  -2 \amp 0 \amp 6
	  \end{array}
	  \right],
	  \bvec = \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  -6 \\ 2
	  \end{array}
	  \right]

	and describe the solution space.

We have the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrrrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \amp 5 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since this system is inconsistent, there are no solutions to the matrix equation.
